From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Wed, 24 Jun 2026 16:42:23 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] jobserver: route all real builds at the engine-global FUSE
 pool
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Retire the transitional per-build kernel pipe. The box-side jobserver module now
just ADVERTISES the engine-global slip pool (the FUSE file /.slopbox-jobserver)
into a build's MAKEFLAGS, in BOTH forms at once so every client connects to the
one pool:
  --jobserver-auth=fifo:/.slopbox-jobserver  (modern make/gcc, and n2)
  --jobserver-fds=R,W                        (a blocking handle pre-opened on that
                                              same path, for older tools)
Both are handles onto the one FUSE-backed pool; the fd-form is per-pid mediated
too, since the engine sees the reader's pid on every acquire. advertise() is
idempotent (a recursive sub-make / nested ninja inherits MAKEFLAGS and joins the
same pool). A build's -jN is now only its LOCAL runner cap; the machine-sized
pool does the system-wide bounding.

n2's client prefers the fifo form and opens its OWN O_NONBLOCK handle, so its
scheduler never stalls, independent of the blocking handles forked tools inherit.

make -j / ninja call advertise() instead of creating a pipe. CASE 12 (parallel,
bounded), 13 (MAKEFLAGS now shows fifo:/.slopbox-jobserver), and 14 (FUSE read)
stay green — real builds now share the engine-global pool. Per-process reaping
and a cross-box sharing test follow.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01XyA6FzC6QGgsrjEYEBJV46
